Ani | Ten years ago (wtf?!), we lived in the same boys’ hostel. Now, at long last, you’re officially a surgeon and leaving the city. I know few people as chaotic as you. Adrak chai looking our absolute worst, extremely chaotic 2am food orders, golden retriever energy, sobfests, space for grounding, thoda comfortable silence when our brains don’t brain. End of an era in this city but so much bful chaos to follow I’m sure. Find your path, carve your niche, may your journey be full of colour and purpose, may there be an abundance of all that you love and want to do with this little life. We (all of your people, whether or not we’ve met) are so proud.

latestPosts.caption:
Trans is only /one/ of so many things we are.
Also my phone’s gallery feels like a movie lol.

💗🌺🏳️‍⚧️

Edwin crossed my mind a few times this month. When I found out a few years ago that he’d passed away, it stung, much as we weren’t particularly close. He came up in conversation recently after all this time, and I realise I have so much unexpressed gratitude.

We first met at a queer safe space in Bangalore when I was 17, utterly confused, in need of someone to give me permission to exist. Edwin, colour in his hair, even more colour on his clothes, was a diva who truly gave zero fks. None whatsoever. I’d never met someone so devoid of shame around their queerness, so free. Winona and Edwin would become my fairy-godmothers, buying me wigs and earrings on Church Street, teaching me how to hold the world’s gaze with a little pride. 

I never felt like I had permission to feel any type of way around his passing - we hadn’t actively remained in touch - but I sometimes think of how we’d meet at Swabhava and then drink at Chin Lung (before it was sanitised/gentrified). “I’d totally kiss you,” says Edwin. “But I’m not 18 yet. Also I like Ian,” says baby-queer-self. My queerness was so valid, so alive, so unserious before any of this. I miss that version. 

Thoroughly disillusioned with religion, we’d laugh at Biblical sayings on digital display from across the road and drink to our childhoods/lives. I’ll never forget it, this very first taste of what it was like to be free, safe in community, held and heard.

This photo was taken at MIC, Manipal at the Pride they organised. I wouldn’t have walked those streets looking this way if it weren’t for him. I never learned details of how he passed but Winona, far closer to him, broke the news. He’d been ill for a while, the meningitis hadn’t gotten better. 

I hope he’s just as queer and unf*ckwithable wherever he is, and knows that I’m so grateful, so grateful.
